# Mindfulness User Story

User Stories for Login/Registration Page

User Story 1: User Registration
Title:
As a user, I want to register by entering my username, email, and password, so that I can create an account.

Acceptance Criteria:

Users can enter valid details and click "Sign Up" to create an account.

An error message is shown if any input is invalid or missing.

Successful registration redirects users to the login page.

Story Points: 3

User Story 2: User Login
Title:
As a user, I want to log in using my email and password, so that I can access my account.

Acceptance Criteria:

Users can log in with correct credentials and are redirected to their dashboard.

An error message is displayed for incorrect credentials.

The login page provides a "Forgot Password" option.

Story Points: 3

User Story 3: Input Validation Feedback
Title:
As a user, I want to receive feedback when I attempt to sign up or log in without entering details, so that I can fix the errors.

Acceptance Criteria:

Error messages are displayed for missing fields on sign-up or login attempts.

Real-time validation highlights invalid input fields before form submission.

Disabled "Sign Up" and "Login" buttons if required fields are empty.

Story Points: 2

User Story 4: Persistent User Data
Title:
As a user, I want my details to be stored in local storage, so that my data persists between sessions.

Acceptance Criteria:

User details are saved in local storage after registration.

Stored credentials are used for authentication during login.

Users can opt to "Stay Logged In" for automatic login in future sessions.

Story Points: 3


User stories for the homepage
User Story 1: Personalized Greeting
Title:
As a user, I want a personalized greeting with my name and a title, so that I feel welcomed and encouraged to meditate.

Acceptance Criteria:

Display “Hello, [username]” followed by the title “Find your perfect meditation.”
The username should be dynamically fetched and displayed upon login.
The greeting should be visually prominent on the homepage.
Story Points: 2

User Story 2: Popular Meditation Cards
Title:
As a user, I want to see popular meditation cards, so that I can explore options based on my preferences.

Acceptance Criteria:

Display meditation cards with an image, title, and short description.
Each card includes categories such as calmness, relaxation, and duration (e.g., 10 or 15 minutes).
Users can click a card to view more details or start the meditation session.
Story Points: 3

User Story 3: Daily Featured Meditation
Title:
As a user, I want a daily featured meditation, so that I can quickly access a recommended session.

Acceptance Criteria:

Showcase one meditation in a dedicated section with an image, title, category, and duration.
The featured meditation updates daily based on recommendations or trending sessions.
Users can tap the featured meditation to start the session immediately.
Story Points: 3

User Story 4: Intuitive Navigation
Title:
As a user, I want intuitive navigation icons, so that I can easily move around the app.

Acceptance Criteria:

Display a logo in the top-left corner that navigates back to the homepage.
Display a settings icon in the top-right corner for accessing user preferences.
Ensure icons are clearly visible and accessible on all screen sizes.
Story Points: 2

user stories for the detailed screen
User Story 1: About Section
Title:
As a user, I want an “About” section for each exercise, so that I can understand its benefits and purpose.

Acceptance Criteria:

Display a brief description of the exercise, explaining its focus and stress-reducing benefits.
The description should be concise yet informative, providing context for users.
Ensure the text is visually distinct and easy to read.
Story Points: 2

User Story 2: Instructions Section
Title:
As a user, I want an “Instructions” section for each exercise, so that I can perform it correctly.

Acceptance Criteria:

Provide step-by-step guidance on posture and breathing techniques for the exercise.
Ensure the instructions are clear and structured for easy understanding.
Include visual aids or bullet points for better readability.
Story Points: 3

User Story 3: Add to Favorites Button
Title:
As a user, I want an “Add to Favorites” button, so that I can easily save an exercise for future practice.

Acceptance Criteria:

Include a prominent “Add to Favorites” button at the bottom of the page.
When clicked, the exercise is added to the user’s favorites list.
Display confirmation feedback (e.g., a checkmark or a message like "Added to Favorites").
Story Points: 2

User Story 4: Navigation Icons
Title:
As a user, I want navigation icons for sharing and going back, so that I can easily manage the exercise page.

Acceptance Criteria:

Display a back icon at the top-left corner to return to the previous screen.
Display a share icon at the top-right corner for sharing the exercise with others.
Ensure icons are visually clear and accessible on all screen sizes.
Story Points: 2

User stories for the add to favorites functionality
User Story 1: Add an Item to Favorites
Title:
As a user, I want to add an item to my Favorites, so that I can save activities or articles I like for quick access later.

Acceptance Criteria:

A heart icon with the text “Add to Favorites” is displayed next to each item.
An outlined heart indicates the item is not in Favorites.
Tapping the button adds the item to the Favorites list, updates the button text to “Remove from Favorites,” and changes the heart icon to filled.
Story Points: 3

User Story 2: Remove an Item from Favorites
Title:
As a user, I want to remove an item from my Favorites, so that I can manage my saved content.

Acceptance Criteria:

The “Remove from Favorites” button with a filled heart is displayed for items already in Favorites.
Tapping the button removes the item from the Favorites list and reverts the heart icon to outlined.
Users can add or remove items anytime, and the button text updates accordingly.
Story Points: 2

User Story 3: My Favorites Screen
Title:
As a user, I want a “My Favorites” screen, so that I can view and manage all my saved items in one place.

Acceptance Criteria:

The “My Favorites” screen displays a list of saved items with their title, category, and duration.
Users can tap any item to view details or start the activity.
The Favorites list remains organized for easy browsing and quick access.
Story Points: 3


User stories for daily reminders
User Story 1: View and Navigate Calendar
Title:
As a user, I want to view the calendar for the current month and navigate between months, so that I can easily select dates for reminders.

Acceptance Criteria:

Display the current month with all days visible.
Provide navigation arrows to move between previous and next months.
Ensure selected dates are visually highlighted.
Story Points: 3

User Story 2: Select a Date and Time for a Reminder
Title:
As a user, I want to select a date and time for a reminder, so that I can schedule it properly.

Acceptance Criteria:

Display a default text “Selected Date: None” and “Selected Time: 20:44” when no date is chosen, but a default time is pre-selected.
Allow users to select a specific date from the calendar.
Provide a time picker for selecting the reminder time.
Story Points: 3

User Story 3: Add a Reminder
Title:
As a user, I want to add a reminder after selecting a time, so that I can schedule it for a future date and time.

Acceptance Criteria:

After selecting a time and date, users can click the “Add Reminder” button to schedule the reminder.
The reminder is saved and displayed in the reminders list.
A confirmation message appears after successfully adding a reminder.
Story Points: 2

User Story 4: View and Manage Reminders List
Title:
As a user, I want to see a list of all my reminders, so that I can manage them easily.

Acceptance Criteria:

Display a list of all reminders with their selected date and time.
Each reminder should be clearly labeled with its scheduled date and time.
Provide an option to delete a reminder by clicking the red “Delete” button next to it.
Story Points: 3

User stories for sharing the exercises
User Story 1: Share Exercises with Others
Title:
As a user, I want to easily share recommended exercises with friends or family, so that I can help others discover helpful activities.

Acceptance Criteria:

Provide a clear share button/icon on the exercise detail page for easy sharing.
When clicked, a share menu appears with multiple platform options (e.g., social media, email, or messaging apps).
Ensure the shared link or message includes the exercise title, description, and a direct link to the exercise page.
Story Points: 3

User Story 2: Copy Exercise Link
Title:
As a user, I want to copy an exercise link, so that I can manually share it with others.

Acceptance Criteria:

Include a “Copy Link” button in the share menu.
When clicked, the exercise URL is copied to the clipboard.
Display a confirmation message (e.g., “Link copied to clipboard”).
Story Points: 2

User Story 3: Customize Shared Message
Title:
As a user, I want to personalize the message before sharing, so that I can add my own thoughts.

Acceptance Criteria:

Before sharing, users can edit a pre-filled message that includes the exercise title and description.
The message preview should be editable in supported platforms (e.g., email, social media posts).
Ensure that the final shared message includes a direct link to the exercise.
Story Points: 3

Create user stories for logout functionality
User Story 1: Clear and Visible Logout Button
Title:
As a user, I want a clear and visible logout button, so that I can easily log out of my account when I’m done using the app.

Acceptance Criteria:

Display a clearly labeled “Logout” button in the app menu or settings page.
The button should be easily accessible without excessive navigation.
The logout button should be visually distinct from other actions (e.g., using a different color or icon).
Story Points: 2

User Story 2: Logout and Redirection
Title:
As a user, I want to be redirected to the login page after logging out, so that I can securely access my account next time.

Acceptance Criteria:

Tapping the Logout button should immediately log the user out.
After logging out, the user is redirected to the login page.
A confirmation message (e.g., “You have been logged out successfully”) should be displayed.
Story Points: 2

User Story 3: Clear User Session Data on Logout
Title:
As a user, I want my session data to be cleared upon logout, so that my account remains secure.

Acceptance Criteria:

User session tokens and authentication details are removed from local storage upon logout.
Any cached personal data (e.g., username, preferences) is cleared.
The app ensures the user must log in again to access their account after logging out.
Story Points: 3


Create user story for change settings
User Story 1: Toggle Between Light and Dark Mode
Title:
As a user, I want to switch between light and dark themes, so that I can reduce eye strain and customize the app’s visual experience.

Acceptance Criteria:

Provide a “Theme” toggle or switch in the settings section for light and dark mode options.
Allow users to switch between themes seamlessly with immediate visual updates.
Ensure the selected theme persists when the user reopens the app.
Story Points: 3

User Story 2: Save and Apply User Preferences
Title:
As a user, I want my selected settings to be saved, so that I don’t have to reset them each time I open the app.

Acceptance Criteria:

The app should store user preferences (e.g., theme selection) in local storage or the user’s account.
When reopening the app, the previously selected settings should be automatically applied.
Users can reset settings to default if needed.
Story Points: 2

User Story 3: Access Settings Easily
Title:
As a user, I want a dedicated settings page, so that I can easily manage my preferences.

Acceptance Criteria:

Include a settings icon in the navigation bar or menu.
Tapping the icon opens a well-organized settings page with customization options.
Ensure settings are easy to understand and modify.
Story Points: 2
